<Author>emaillittlebird
<Content>Disappointed We booked a three-night stay online and, with flights from the UK, got a deal of 拢270 per person for the holiday, so pretty average for a city break. As this hotel is sold as 4 star, we expected something a little bit special. Our room was in the modern part of the hotel, which was clearly undergoing some refurbishment works as the place was crawling with workmen. As we went up to our room, the lifts and carpets were covered in dusty footprints, which didn't seem to be cleaned away for our entire stay. Reception staff weren't particularly friendly, although did humour our lousy Spanish.Our room was the most disappointing part of the holiday - on entering, it looked impressive, but on closer inspection it wasn't as great as we thought. The room was very cold and dark. The only window looked out into the atrium where the lift shafts were, so, even on the 7th floor, we got very little natural light  had to go outside to see what the weather was like. The skirting boards were all scuffed and the laminate peeling off. We couldn't get the TV to work (and requests to reception to sort it were ignored for 2 days), so looked at the plug socket which was (quite dangerously) falling out of the wall. And the bathroom, although reasonably smart with good quality towels, was tatty with several stains to the sink area and grouting.Each morning we were woken early by the noise of housekeeping wheeling trolleys about and shouting to each other. One morning, a chambermaid even came into the room after one brief knock at the door at 8:30am - maybe we should have put a DND sign up, but you don't expect to be disturbed quite so early.The saving graces of this hotel were, firstly, its location - 10 mins from the Catalunya Square at the top of the Ramblas, and an area we felt safe in. And, secondly, the terraces on top of both buildings. Our tip would be, use the modern building's sun terrace for the pool and loungers during the day (the pool wasn't huge, but big enough for a couple of people to just about swim), and use the old building's terrace at night for drinks (not too expensive for a 4 star hotel bar) but not for the pool (very small).And one non-hotel tip - dine at the Attic on the Ramblas (top end towards Catalunya, Gotic side - look for the staff in orange who guide you up) and ask to be seated on the terrace. Really good, reasonably-priced food, especially for the fantastic location. 
